While we’re on the subject: if you haven’t read Dirty Daddy or seen the Comedy Central roast and you’re grieving Saget, I would recommend waiting a solid 2 weeks before diving into those/watching his stand up. It is a jarring, yet interesting, contrast from Danny Tanner.

To say he was “America’s Dad” seems accurate to me because he embodied so many difficult, problematic, heartwarming, wonderful, and nostalgic roles all at once for Millennials; roles that parents—even our own parents—also embody for their children in real life.

Also: the stuff we learned about Saget after Full House—the crude humor, the Comedy Central Roast, & Dirty Daddy—and how we had to reconcile that with our image of Danny Tanner mirrors how we all have to, on some level, grapple with the contractions of our actual parents.

The outpouring of Millennial grief from Bob Saget’s death is entirely appropriate considering that he, in the form of Danny Tanner, kind of raised us through the television screen. And for the comedy-buffs among us, he kept parenting us long after Full House ended.

As an adult, my parents & I are actually *friends* and we’re *great friends* at that. Sure we have our moments, everyone does, but I think we’re close because being an only combined with their parenting style meant that they always regarded me as a whole person.

I’m aware that for some people that sort of situation can be harmful because you might have to grow up too fast. But in my case, I feel like in retrospect it was actually amazing for me. My parents struck a great balance between letting me be a kid and regarding me as an equal.

Like I spent so much time around my parents and their friends as a kid. I adopted their interests, music taste, sense of humor, mannerisms, etc. over those of my peers. I was excited to get my hands on the latest Train or Floating Men album, not the latest Barbie or whatever.

Someone should research this (if it’s not already been done), but I think it’s because not having siblings pretty much guarantees that one of your biggest primary socializing agents is going to be adults. Not just your parents, but also their friends.

When I was a kid I hated not having siblings, but now as an adult I’ve really come to value the unique bond I have with my parents because I was an only. I’m like…their friend now. We buddies, pals, homies. It’s dope.
